---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-philippines', text: 'Leaving Philippine Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'ofw-considerations', text: 'OFW Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Asia Insurance', href: '/best/asia-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Middle East Insurance', href: '/best/middle-east-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'gulfNetwork', header: 'Gulf Network' },
  { key: 'globalNetwork', header: 'Global Network' },
  { key: 'phCoverage', header: 'PH Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', gulfNetwork: 'Excellent', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', phCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'PHP 9,500/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', gulfNetwork: 'Excellent', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', phCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'PHP 11,000/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', gulfNetwork: 'Good', globalNetwork: 'Strong', phCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'PHP 9,000/mo' },
  { provider: 'Pacific Cross', gulfNetwork: 'Limited', globalNetwork: 'Limited', phCoverage: 'Included', price: 'PHP 6,500/mo' },
  { provider: 'Maxicare', gulfNetwork: 'Limited', globalNetwork: 'Limited', phCoverage: 'Included', price: 'PHP 5,000/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Filipino Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Filipino expats and OFWs. Find coverage for the Gulf, US, Singapore, and other destinations."
  headline="Best Insurance for Filipino Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Millions of Filipinos work abroad as OFWs. Here's how to stay protected in the Gulf, US, Singapore, and beyond—with coverage that works when you visit home."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/filipino-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Filipino overseas workers (OFWs) are found worldwide—from the Gulf states to the US, Singapore, Hong Kong, and beyond. Understanding employer coverage gaps and PhilHealth limitations abroad is critical. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Filipino expats. Excellent Gulf and US networks, comprehensive coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with outstanding worldwide networks. Top-tier service.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong value option.</li>
    <li><strong>Pacific Cross:</strong> Philippines-based insurer with international products. Familiar brand, includes PH.</li>
    <li><strong>Maxicare:</strong> Major Philippine HMO with some international options. Best for those prioritizing home coverage.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Beyond Employer Coverage"
    description="Many OFWs rely solely on employer-provided insurance. This coverage ends when employment ends—and may have significant gaps. Personal international insurance provides continuity and comprehensive protection."
    buttonText="Get Personal Coverage Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-philippines">Leaving Philippine Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    The Philippines has both public and private healthcare. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>PhilHealth</h3>
  <p>
    PhilHealth is the Philippine national health insurance program. OFWs can maintain PhilHealth membership while abroad, but coverage only applies to healthcare received in the Philippines. It doesn't cover treatment in your host country.
  </p>

  <h3>PhilHealth for OFWs</h3>
  <p>
    OFWs can continue PhilHealth contributions for coverage during home visits. The contribution is relatively affordable and ensures access to Philippine hospitals when you return. This supplements, not replaces, international coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Philippine Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Private HMOs (Maxicare, Medicard, Intellicare) primarily cover Philippine facilities. Some offer international products, but networks abroad are limited compared to global insurers.
  </p>

  <h3>Employer Coverage Abroad</h3>
  <p>
    Most OFWs receive employer-provided health insurance. Quality and coverage vary significantly by employer and destination. Understand your employer coverage before assuming it's adequate.
  </p>

  <h2 id="ofw-considerations">OFW Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Overseas Filipino Workers have specific healthcare considerations:
  </p>

  <h3>Gulf Countries</h3>
  <p>
    Saudi Arabia, UAE, Kuwait, and Qatar host millions of Filipino workers. Employers are typically required to provide health insurance, but coverage quality varies. Domestic workers may have limited coverage. Supplemental international insurance fills gaps.
  </p>

  <h3>Employer Insurance Limitations</h3>
  <p>
    Employer coverage typically ends with employment. Job changes, contract completion, or termination leaves you uninsured. Personal international insurance provides continuity during transitions.
  </p>

  <h3>Home Leave Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    When visiting the Philippines, you need healthcare access. PhilHealth provides basic coverage. International insurance with Philippine coverage ensures comprehensive access during visits.
  </p>

  <h3>Family Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    Many OFWs support families in the Philippines. International insurance can cover dependents in the Philippines while covering you abroad—or provide coverage when family joins you overseas.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">OWWA and POEA</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      OFWs are covered by OWWA (Overseas Workers Welfare Administration) programs. OWWA provides some benefits including repatriation and limited medical assistance. This is supplementary—not comprehensive health insurance.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage ideal for Filipino OFWs. Excellent networks in the Gulf states, US, and Singapore—key Filipino destinations. Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    24/7 service available. Philippines coverage can be added for home visits.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Filipino expats wanting reliable coverage that works in the Gulf and other major destinations.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent worldwide networks. Outstanding service quality. Strong presence in the Gulf and Asia.
  </p>

  <p>
    Higher pricing reflects premium quality. Philippines coverage available as add-on.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Filipino professionals who want top-tier coverage and service.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong networks in key destinations. Good value for comprehensive coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Filipino expats seeking good value with reliable global coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Pacific Cross</h3>
  <p>
    Pacific Cross is a Philippines-based insurer offering international products. Familiar brand, Philippines coverage included automatically. International networks are more limited than global specialists.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Filipino expats who prefer familiar Philippine service with integrated home coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Maxicare</h3>
  <p>
    Maxicare is the largest Philippine HMO and offers some international products. Best Philippine networks, familiar service. International coverage is limited compared to global insurers.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> OFWs who prioritize Philippine coverage for family and frequent home visits.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Don't Rely Only on Employer Coverage"
    description="Your employer's insurance ends when your contract ends. Personal international insurance provides continuity during job changes and comprehensive coverage your employer plan may lack."
    buttonText="Get Personal Coverage"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Filipino workers are found worldwide with specific concentrations:
  </p>

  <h3>Gulf States (Saudi Arabia, UAE, Qatar, Kuwait)</h3>
  <p>
    Millions of Filipinos work in the Gulf. Employer insurance is typically mandatory but varies in quality. Healthcare infrastructure is excellent in major cities. Domestic workers may have less comprehensive employer coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    Large Filipino-American community, especially in California. US healthcare is expensive—comprehensive coverage is essential. Many Filipino healthcare workers in the US have employer insurance, but personal coverage provides continuity.
  </p>

  <h3>Singapore</h3>
  <p>
    Significant Filipino community. Singapore requires employer-provided insurance for work permit holders. Coverage varies by employer—verify adequacy and consider supplementation.
  </p>

  <h3>Hong Kong</h3>
  <p>
    Large domestic worker population. Employer must provide insurance, but coverage may be basic. Hong Kong healthcare is expensive—ensure adequate coverage.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does PhilHealth cover me abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. PhilHealth only covers healthcare in the Philippines. Maintain PhilHealth for home visits, but you need separate international insurance for your host country.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is my employer's insurance enough?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">It depends. Review your employer coverage carefully. Many OFW employer plans have limitations. Personal insurance supplements gaps and provides continuity between jobs.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage for my family in PH?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Some international insurers cover dependents in different countries. Pacific Cross and Maxicare include Philippines coverage. PhilHealth can also cover family members.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What happens when my contract ends?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Employer insurance ends with employment. Personal international insurance continues regardless. This is critical during job searches and transitions.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Pacific Cross or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Pacific Cross offers Philippine familiarity and includes PH. Cigna has stronger global networks, especially in the Gulf. Choose based on destination priorities.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What does OWWA cover?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">OWWA provides welfare benefits including some medical assistance and repatriation. It's not comprehensive health insurance—it's supplementary protection for OFWs.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Filipino OFWs need to look beyond employer coverage. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> offers excellent networks in the Gulf and other key destinations. <strong>Bupa Global</strong> provides premium coverage for those who want the best.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Pacific Cross</strong> suits those who prefer Philippine familiarity with integrated home coverage. <strong>Maxicare</strong> works for those prioritizing Philippine family coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Maintain PhilHealth for home visits. But don't rely on employer coverage alone—personal international insurance protects you during job transitions and fills coverage gaps.
  </p>

</PageShell>
